Okay.

00:06:05.840 --> 00:06:06.900
Great.

00:06:06.930 --> 00:06:10.070
Welcome to EPUB 3 Bootcamp.

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:13.320
I'm going to get you up to
date on the EPUB 3 anatomy,

00:06:13.370 --> 00:06:16.690
and then I'll show you how
to use some EPUB technology

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:18.880
to create pop-ups in iBooks.

00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:23.460
As I mentioned,
EPUB is really just web technology.

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:26.040
HTML, CSS, JavaScript.

00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:29.820
And then we're bundling it
together and zipping it up and

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:32.810
giving it an extension of .epub.

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:37.340
I actually think it's easiest
to think of a book as a website.

00:06:37.340 --> 00:06:39.870
But then you need to ask, okay, well,
what's the difference

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:40.990
between a website and a book?

00:06:41.070 --> 00:06:43.920
And there's a lot of different
answers out there for it,

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:46.640
but I'm going to give you
a technical explanation.

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:49.940
And to do that,
I'm going to show you an EPUB.

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:55.860
So here's our EPUB,
and I'm going to unzip it.

00:06:55.970 --> 00:07:01.520
And inside, there are two folders,
the OEBPS and the MetaINF.

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:04.700
We're only going to worry
about the OEBPS folder today,

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:09.970
because that is the folder that contains
all of the content of your book.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:13.070
So inside of it is all that web
technology I told you about.

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:16.570
Your XHTML,
that's the main content of your book.

00:07:16.660 --> 00:07:18.000
Your text.

00:07:18.030 --> 00:07:21.640
It also includes your styling,
so your CSS and your fonts.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:25.300
And your media, so your images, audio,
video.

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:29.260
This is all the standard web content,
but in addition to that,

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:33.870
there's also two EPUB-specific files,
and this is what's making it a book.

00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:37.810
There is the OPF file
and the NAV document.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:41.410
Now,
the OPF file is a carryover from EPUB 2.

00:07:41.810 --> 00:07:45.580
The NAV document is an entirely
new document in EPUB 3,

00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:47.280
so we'll spend most of our time on that.

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:49.860
First, though, let's look at the OPF.

00:07:51.530 --> 00:07:55.140
The OPF contains all of the
information about your book,

00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:58.720
including your package version,
that's which version

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:00.400
of EPUB you're using.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:03.320
It also includes the
metadata for your book,

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:06.720
a manifest which lists all
of the files in your book,

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:11.160
and a spine which defines the
linear reading order of your book.

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:15.100
So first of all,
because we're making EPUB 3 today,

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:17.020
we need to update our package version.

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:21.790
So this is the package element,
the version set to 2.0,

00:08:21.790 --> 00:08:24.050
we have to make it a 3.0.

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:26.370
Are you ready?

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:29.840
3.0, okay, really hard, right?

00:08:29.910 --> 00:08:33.590
All right, but that does set us up for
needing to make some other

00:08:33.590 --> 00:08:37.610
adjustments and other changes,
starting with the metadata.

00:08:38.680 --> 00:08:43.110
So in EPUB 2, you are required to provide
three metadata items,

00:08:43.110 --> 00:08:46.540
the title, the language, and the ID.

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:51.780
But in EPUB 3, you're also required to
provide the date modified.

00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:55.150
So to run through the metadata
element for this book,

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:58.440
The Hobbit, we have the titles,
The Hobbit.

00:08:58.470 --> 00:09:02.800
We have the ID for the book,
which is usually the ISBN number,

00:09:02.850 --> 00:09:08.410
the language the book is written in,
in this case, English, and our new item,

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:10.300
DC terms modified.

00:09:10.300 --> 00:09:15.620
This is the date your
book was last modified,

00:09:15.620 --> 00:09:17.790
and it's really important
that you include it so that

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.700
You have an idea of version control,
so that whether it's you with the book

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:25.300
with multiple versions or if you've
given someone else multiple versions,

00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:28.740
we have a sense of which one
is the most up to date and then

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:31.490
therefore probably the most correct.

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:33.770
And The Hobbit's a really
good example of this.

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:38.470
The Hobbit was written in 1937,
and since then, it has undergone many

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:40.280
revisions and additions.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:44.340
So it's really important as you're
moving into the digital world that

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:49.280
you include that date modified so
that I can tell and the iBooksor can

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:52.970
tell what the most recent version is.

00:09:53.150 --> 00:09:56.500
So metadata,
much the same as it was in EPUB 2,

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:59.050
but be sure you include
your DC terms modified.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:01.720
Next is the manifest.

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:05.440
Again, the manifest,
mostly unchanged since EPUB 2.

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:08.080
And this looks like a
lot of text up there,

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:12.610
but really all it is is a listing of
all the files that make up your book.

00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:16.730
That's your XHTML, your CSS, your fonts,
all of that content we

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:18.660
were discussing earlier.

00:10:20.120 --> 00:10:22.630
In EPUB 3, though,
we now have something called

00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:24.260
the properties attribute.

00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:29.070
The properties attribute
allows you to further identify

00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:31.640
key files in your manifest.

00:10:31.640 --> 00:10:35.040
And I have two really good
examples of that here.

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:38.250
One is for the navigation document.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:42.800
The navigation document is
a vital file in your book,

00:10:42.890 --> 00:10:45.840
and so you need to call
that out as being special.

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:48.440
So to do that,
you add the properties attribute

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:50.020
and give it a value of nav.

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:55.050
Another example is for the cover image.

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:59.680
In EPUB 2, the cover image was
defined in the metadata,

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:03.130
but in EPUB 3,
all you need to do is add the properties

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:09.460
attribute with the value of cover image
on the actual cover in the manifest.

00:11:10.010 --> 00:11:14.360
So manifest largely unchanged in EPUB 3,
just be sure you use the properties

00:11:14.740 --> 00:11:16.550
attribute where required.

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:18.360
And finally, the spine.

00:11:18.410 --> 00:11:21.440
The spine is unchanged in EPUB 3,
but it is a very,

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:25.940
very important part of the OPF file,
so I'm going to cover it here.

00:11:25.970 --> 00:11:28.340
It lists the linear
reading order of your book.

00:11:28.570 --> 00:11:31.390
That's all of the content
documents of your book,

00:11:31.530 --> 00:11:34.450
and it's defining the order and
literally binding it together,

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:38.010
much like the spine of a physical book.

00:11:38.850 --> 00:11:41.700
And the markup for the
spine is essentially a list.

00:11:41.790 --> 00:11:45.330
So now we have the spine
element and we have chapter 1,

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:47.160
chapter 2, chapter 3.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:50.250
It's very simple but very important.

00:11:50.650 --> 00:11:52.750
And that's the OPF file in EPUB 3.

00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:57.810
So we've updated the version number,
we added modified date to the metadata,

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:01.360
we added the properties
attribute to the manifest,

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:03.180
and we provided a spine.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:08.200
Now I know there's at least a
few EPUB veterans out there,

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:12.990
and you may have noticed that
I didn't mention the guide element.

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:16.220
The guide element is actually
deprecated in EPUB 2,

00:12:16.310 --> 00:12:21.410
but it has a replacement in
EPUB 3's navigation document.

00:12:22.170 --> 00:12:26.860
The navigation document
replaces EPUB 2's NCX file.

00:12:26.970 --> 00:12:30.260
And if any of you have ever
written an NCX file by hand,

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:31.780
you can rejoice now.

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:33.200
You don't have to do it again.

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:36.280
Yes, I knew there would be a couple.

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:36.860
Okay.

00:12:36.860 --> 00:12:43.290
And the navigation document provides
all of the information about your book,

00:12:43.380 --> 00:12:48.100
or about how to navigate your book,
including the table of contents,

00:12:48.140 --> 00:12:49.730
landmarks, and a page list.

00:12:49.870 --> 00:12:53.000
And those are the three
we'll cover today.

00:12:53.150 --> 00:12:55.960
All of these, the table, contents,
landmarks, and page lists,

00:12:56.020 --> 00:13:00.180
are created using an HTML5 nav element.

00:13:00.410 --> 00:13:05.280
The nav element allows you to
actually define an order for a list.

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:06.840
So here we have the nav element.

00:13:07.050 --> 00:13:11.880
Inside of it is our ordered list,
and then we have individual list items.

00:13:12.050 --> 00:13:20.490
Note that each list item has both
text and a link for that text.

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:24.900
Now because you're using this
nav structure for all three,

00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:28.900
your table of contents, your landmarks,
and your page list,

00:13:29.020 --> 00:13:32.700
you also need to provide a way
to differentiate between those.

00:13:32.800 --> 00:13:36.380
And you do that using
the epub type attribute.

00:13:36.990 --> 00:13:40.880
The EPUB type attribute is
a new attribute in EPUB 3,

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:43.690
and it provides additional
semantic meaning to any

00:13:43.980 --> 00:13:45.620
element it's on in your book.

00:13:45.740 --> 00:13:49.410
There's a whole variety of
pre-existing values for this,

00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:53.680
but for today, when we're discussing
the navigation document,

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:57.280
we'll focus on table of contents,
landmarks, and page list.

00:14:01.760 --> 00:14:04.160
And we add it directly
to the nav element.

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:09.020
So here's our nav element with
the EPUB type of TOC for table

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:11.510
of contents added in there.

00:14:12.060 --> 00:14:15.310
So let's go ahead and make
a real table of contents.

00:14:15.550 --> 00:14:19.780
This is a table of contents in iBooks.

00:14:19.930 --> 00:14:22.840
So you have chapter one.

00:14:23.130 --> 00:14:28.140
On page 3, nested under it is figure 1,
and back out again is chapter 2.

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:32.190
Now your job is to provide the
text for this table of contents and

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:34.540
to provide the structure for it.

00:14:34.540 --> 00:14:39.890
iBooks' job is to provide
the page numbers for you.

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:44.330
So to create this structure,
you're going to use that nav element.

00:14:44.330 --> 00:14:46.920
And you're going to give
it an EPUB type of TOC,

00:14:47.010 --> 00:14:48.480
for table of contents.

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:51.910
And inside of that,
you have the ordered list

00:14:51.910 --> 00:14:54.030
with your list items.

00:14:54.040 --> 00:14:58.440
So the first list item is chapter 1,
and it has a link associated

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:02.560
with it for chapter1.xhtml,
so that when the reader touches

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.760
chapter 1 in the table of contents,
they'll be taken to the

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:09.260
chapter 1 content document.

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:12.910
Now, I didn't close out the
list item for this,

00:15:12.910 --> 00:15:15.730
because instead,
I'm nesting under it a new

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:17.850
