00:17:33.630 --> 00:17:35.240
Next is the page list.

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:39.660
Page list allows you to define
custom page numbers for your book.

00:17:39.780 --> 00:17:42.000
When do you want to define
custom page numbers?

00:17:42.120 --> 00:17:44.420
Well, there's a few reasons.

00:17:44.560 --> 00:17:49.680
One, in flowing books,
the number of perceived pages for your

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:52.720
book depends on a few different factors.

00:17:52.910 --> 00:17:55.720
For one, the device size.

00:17:55.720 --> 00:17:58.650
Another, the font size.

00:17:59.060 --> 00:18:02.250
In this example,
we have the same book on both

00:18:02.250 --> 00:18:04.450
the iPad and on the iPhone.

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:11.540
But on the iPad, you have 398 pages,
and on the iPhone, you have 1,900 pages.

00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:17.690
So this can pose a particular problem
if you're trying to send someone to a

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:22.950
very specific location in your book,
because everyone's going to have

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:25.330
a different concept of the paging.

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:29.950
For instance, let's say you're in a
classroom and the teacher says,

00:18:30.090 --> 00:18:34.610
"Class, turn to page 82 of White Fang."

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:37.110
Now all of the students who
are reading digital readers

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:42.020
are going to have a different
concept of what that page 82 is.

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:46.100
But they're going to be fine
if you provide a page list.

00:18:46.220 --> 00:18:50.990
Because your page list is
going to set a standard paging,

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:56.510
sets demarcations,
and it will also provide custom

00:18:56.630 --> 00:18:58.410
page numbers if you like.

00:18:58.580 --> 00:19:03.370
So the best way to show this is to look
at the table of contents in iBooks.

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:07.200
So this is the table of
contents we just made.

00:19:07.390 --> 00:19:10.450
Chapter 1 is on page 3,
figure 1 is on page 6,

00:19:10.530 --> 00:19:12.290
and chapter 2 is on page 9.

00:19:12.290 --> 00:19:17.370
When you apply the page list to this,
you can make these page numbers

00:19:17.370 --> 00:19:18.780
whatever you need them to be.

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:21.860
Now this example is a little zany,
but it gives you an

00:19:22.100 --> 00:19:23.410
idea of what you can do.

00:19:23.410 --> 00:19:30.320
Chapter 1 is page 1, figure 1 is intro,
chapter 2 is Roman numeral 4.

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:32.010
So it's up to you.

00:19:32.690 --> 00:19:37.280
Now, in fixed layout books,
the pagination is different.

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:40.630
People experience the
exact same number of pages,

00:19:40.630 --> 00:19:44.370
no matter what their device,
no matter what their orientation,

00:19:44.430 --> 00:19:49.560
but there still may be a time when you
want to define custom page numbers.

00:19:49.920 --> 00:19:53.130
And an example of this is,
let's say you have an

00:19:53.130 --> 00:19:56.870
existing print book,
and you want the digital book,

00:19:56.870 --> 00:20:00.630
its page numbering to match
up with the print book.

00:20:00.630 --> 00:20:03.500
To do that,
you would provide a page list.

00:20:03.670 --> 00:20:07.270
So now, you know, normally in iBooks,
the cover page by default

00:20:07.270 --> 00:20:09.490
would be page one,
but your print book,

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:12.700
it's not going to have
the cover page number one.

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:17.030
So by adding a page list to this,
I now can have my last page

00:20:17.030 --> 00:20:19.150
be Roman numeral seven.

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:24.000
And this means that the reader can
scrub that thumbnail nav along the

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.160
bottom and see the pages that they
want and navigate to it that way.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:33.370
Creating a page list for both
flowing and fixed layout books,

00:20:33.370 --> 00:20:35.400
again, we're using that nav element.

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:40.650
We're setting an EPUB type of page list,
and now all of the text that's

00:20:40.770 --> 00:20:45.270
in our list items defines the
text for our page numbers.

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:48.510
So in this case,
we have intro for the first item,

00:20:48.510 --> 00:20:53.460
we have the next page unnumbered,
and then we start a numbering of 1, 2,

00:20:53.460 --> 00:20:54.520
and 3.

00:20:54.690 --> 00:20:58.610
Now, your linking structure is going
to change a little bit between a

00:20:58.710 --> 00:21:01.030
flowing book and a fixed layout book.

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:03.590
And that's because in
a fixed layout book,

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:07.280
you have one content document per page.

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:11.080
So when you're linking to that,
you're just going to be

00:21:11.080 --> 00:21:15.140
linking to page 1x HTML,
page 2x HTML, and so on.

00:21:15.390 --> 00:21:21.800
But in a flowing book,
you have one XHTML document per chapter,

00:21:21.890 --> 00:21:24.800
and you're going to have many
pages within that chapter.

00:21:24.950 --> 00:21:30.380
So you need to provide markers within it,
and really IDs within that to

00:21:30.380 --> 00:21:32.800
mark the start of each page.

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:35.010
And it looks like this.

00:21:35.550 --> 00:21:37.480
So here's my HTML document.

00:21:37.790 --> 00:21:42.580
I have a paragraph in there,
and I've added the ID of P1 for page 1.

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:47.860
And that references, then,
the chapter 1 XHTML with

00:21:47.890 --> 00:21:50.110
a fragment ID of P1.

00:21:50.200 --> 00:21:52.100
So that is PageList.

00:21:52.490 --> 00:21:56.300
It's easy to create,
and it can be very useful.

